"Please, please not this!" Queen Arvyn pleaded. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with the royal advisor standing beside him. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, the Ice King couldn't help but frown.
The baby girl looked like her mother: she had light blue eyes and snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair mixed in. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, until then, he only had sons.
"You have only two choices: either kill this child or abandon her in the wilderness. Alvin, this is your punishment," he said viciously, as if her name were poison. He always spoke like that.
The Frostland was not always a kingdom. It was once divided into two, north and south. The northern part established a non-magical kingdom, while the southern part was filled with realms of fantastical power. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms engaged in endless war until the south proposed a ceasefire.
At the time, the South was already despondent, and royal members were willing to do anything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed marrying off their only princess to the North, where she would become the queen and bear a son who would be the future king. Afterwards, the South would merge with the North to form a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and thus Princess Alwen married Prince Akul.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me. Lock me up, exile me, even kill me," Queen Elvine pleaded, hugging her child tightly.
The Ice King lowered his gaze to look at the queen, his eyes brimming with disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he might feel a shred of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, caring for him during his most despondent moments and bearing him children.
"Okay. The child can stay in the palace," the queen sighed in relief upon hearing what Ice King said. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Arvin both wore expressions of fear. She slowly lowered her head and looked at the floor. "Your wish is my command, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Alvin. Afterward, he commanded the guards to bring Alvin to the execution ground where all the citizens could see.
When the guards led her to the execution site, the citizens saw their only queen—also the kindest of queens—about to be put to death, and felt extremely enraged. Some cried, some shouted trying to attack the guards, and others wanted to know why this was happening; but they all shared the same question.
"Release her!"
"Why are they treating her like this?"
As Alvin approached the wooden stake, the scariest person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the burning. Queen Alvin would be burned alive. No one should be executed by burning, not even criminals. In the Frostland, burning was the most cruel punishment.
Erlwin was tied to a wooden stake, and the king began to tell how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frostland refused to believe it and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner set the stake alight, and a tear rolled down the former queen's face.
